Introduction about the dataset :

This data set is for world universities ranking. It is prepared by The Times Higher Education World University Ranking.It is available on Kaggle. It contains the rank for the years from 2011 to 2016. The number of variables in this dataset is 14 variables with 2603 rows. The description for each variable is provided in the text file attached with this one.

Univariate Analysis:

We have a dataset containing from 14 variables and 2603 rows. The main features of interest in our dataset is we have the same rank repeated for 6 consecutive years and thus will help us to see and track the change over the years like we did in the income and the ratio of international students. The dataset also has multiple variables which will help us to make a lot of analysis to get the full picture.

The distributions are almost predicted except that the citations factor had new countries with high rate. The increase in percentage of international students was expected over years. All other distributions were close.

I have a lot of operations on the data to be clean. Numbers were cleaned from commas and dashes. Factor variables then converted to integers to create nice and smooth histograms.

Bivariate Plots Section

In the bivariate analysis I think it is better to look at the correlation between the total score variable and other variables. The total score variable is the one which decides the final order of the rank. I will choose four variables to be investigated versus total score variable. They are research, teaching, student staff ratio and income. This will help us to see what is the most variable which affects the score of the universu=ity to be higher.

Relation between the total score and teaching:

This is investigated for the whole dataset only.

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  df$teaching and df$total_score
## t = 69.226, df = 1199, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.8824326 0.9051315
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.8943562

Wow ,It seems like a very nice scatter plot which indicates a high correlation factor between the two values.

We can use the function cor.test to calculate this value. The result was 0.894. The result is the same if calculated for the dataset of the top 200 universities.

Relation between the total score and income :

## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation

The results here are not as expected. The correlation factor is 0.226 from cor.test. It seems that not all the high ranked universities are interested in this variable. This is obvious because when we look at the dataset we can see that there are a lot of missed values in this column.

I do not know what is the reason behind this. May be ,there is no information at the organization which conducted the survey about this or the university itself is not interested in tracking this variable. Any way it seems that this variable is still not having the best effect on the rank or at least we know that universities are not interested in it.

The correlation of these two variables for the top 200 universities is 0.225 and so this correation is not biased by the rank of year 2016

Bivariate Analysis :

Specific parameters were chosen to conduct our analysis on. The teaching and research had a positive and strong corelation with the total score variable. However, The income had a weak correlation and the student-staff ratio had a weak and a negative correlation with the total score variable. That was unexpected.

Multivariate Plots Section :

I think a good way to look at the change made by each country is very hard, so we will choose the leading countries as concluded from the univariate analysis. These countries are USA , UK, Germany, Australia.

One good way to look at the trend of these countries over years is to look at the mean of each variable achieved by each country. Removing the missed value will not affect the calculated mean value for each variable.I will work for the whole dataset and so themean value will give us an overall indication for the education in a country.

Looking at the mean value will help us to see a clear graph with less details. However, This will give us an overall view of each of these countries over each year. We can see if a country made some improvement in one of the variables or another country lost its position in one of the variables.

From the bivariate analysis, we concluded that the two variables : teaching and research has a strong correlation with the total score. We will look at the trend of these two variables in addition to citations variable.

Citations trend for top countries :

We can see that USA is the highest and we can see that there is a dip at 2012 for the four countries. It is a strange thing and needs some analysis. The rank for 2012 involves 400 universities and nothing strange in our dataset. I can not understand the reason behind this.

Also, There is a huge dip for Japan in 2016 and the Germanys performance is improving to be the second one in 2016.

Teaching trend for top countries :

Japan had a good start at 2011 but it had a dip in 2016 again like citations. Germany again made some achivement and eventually they are equal to USA . All countries went down from 2011 to 2012 as usual. All countries wentdown from 2015 to 2016 except Germany. Good news for Germany.

Research trend for top countries :

Japan was the highest in 2011 but the least in 2016 . Warning for Japan !!. Germany is the best in 2016.

Number of international students :

We can make multivariate analysis by getting the number of international students from the given ratio of the international students.

Then, we can plot the trend for the seleced countries over years for the total summation of international students.

USA and UK are the leading countries in the number of international students. UK has a big jump from 2015 to 2016. Japan is the least.

Multivariate Analysis:

The dataset contained the rank for different years and this was a good feature to look at the trend of each country. One observation is that Germany is making some improvements while Japan lost a lot although it was the leading country in 2011 for some variables.

The number of international students is very high in USA and UK. We could make better analysis if we had information about the number of scholarships for each country and also the expenses of each university.

Reflection

This was an interesting exploration through the dataset. The dataset was not so clean. Some variables were not integers and were not even clean integers. The cleaning of this dataset took some time. The dataset had a good thing which was the information repeated for 6 years and this was interesting to look at the trend of a country over the 6 years.

A future work that can be done with dataset is to fill some missed values and to add some other variables like the expenses of a university to be able to look at the relation between the expenses and the rank of the university and number of students. Also the percentage of employment can be involved also like other datasets.

A future work also is to complete investigation for other leading countries like France, Spain and Netherlands and make trends like we did for the sake of comparison.
